abstract: The railroad interests in Virginia, Tennesce and Kentucky, which initiated the project of a transatlantic steamship line by sending the lion. WM. abstract: HOT AGAIN.-Yesterday and Saturday were exceedingly close, hot days. There was little air stirring, and that little seemed to be about as hot as the rest. abstract: From a communication presented to the French Academy of Sciences. by M. abstract: An old Negro was kidnapped in this place on Wednesday morning last, by some man from Evansville, on the allegation that the African was from Kentucky. The man from Evansville, it appears, followed the Negro up from some point on the Evansville and Crawfordsville Raliroad, and arrested him, as he said, "on suspicion" of being a fugitive, Immediately after the train arrived in Terre Hauto.

abstract: At the present time we look with interest to each fresh arrival from the north, expecting news thereby from the field of diplomatic action in the Gulf of Pechcle. abstract: A meeting favorable to the nomination of GERRIT SMITH for Governor, was held on Wednesday, at Peterboro, the village where Mr. SMITH resides. A sketch of its proceedings will be found in another part of this morning's TIMES. It will he seen that the sentiments of Mr. SMITH'S friends were not harmonious. Strange as it may be, the spirit of party expediency was not altogether wanting.

abstract: Among the highly important and interesting intelligence brought together in the TIMES of this morning, will be found an announcement of the final ratification of the Cass-Yrissari Treaty. Two modifications are annexed, neither of which materially affects its purport, and since the leading stipulations remain as dictated by our Government, we are to presame that no difficulty will be made in regard to secondary points.

abstract: The United States steamship Granada, Lieut. BERRYMAN, arrived, on Thursday evening, from Aspinwall, which port she left on the 19th, via Greytown on the 20th, and Key West, where she called on the 25th. She brings only a small number of passengers, among whom are Messrs. WEBSTER, ALLEN, and GOTTEL, agents of Commodore VANDERBILT, who went to Nicaragua to obtain the ratification of the contract for the possession of the Isthmus transit route.
